  &lt;Comment&gt;
    &lt;Title&gt;Poor practice&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Anonymous&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;My GP referred me to Salford Royal after stating I could have cancer.  She followed up on the same day with a letter to me directing me to the cancer research website relating to urgent referrals.  I then received a letter from Salford Royal stating  that a telephone appointment had been arranged with a consultant.  The letter did not state which department the consultant was in and the only telephone number on the letter was for the appointment booking department.  The consultant booked me in for a scan.  Since then I have heard nothing.  I contacted the number on the letter and was told I would have to phone the consultant's secretary and was put through to her.  This is where the poor practice starts.  The secretary is not available to answer the phone and has left a recorded message stating that she is unable to do so.  In the message she says that if I need to speak to someone to phone another number as voicemail messages that get left are not being picked up.  The number she says I have to phone is for the booking department who say I need to speak to the secretary.  Clearly I have been left unable to speak to anyone to chase up my results.  Your response, no doubt, will be to contact Pals or make a complaint but that takes time and resources.  I appreciate that we are all having to find ways of working safely through the pandemic but I do feel that patients should be able to speak to a member of staff in relation to getting results (particularly if the results could be bad news).  It is now six months since the first lockdown and I feel this has given you more than enough time to ensure staff have facilities and resources to enable staff to work from home, and be able to carry out duties like speaking to patients or at the very least make it clear in correspondence what the time frame is for getting results and how they will be delivered.  I am worried that I have cancer and have no idea when I will hear anything and I am unable to make contact with anyone.  This is having a negative impact on my health and I do not see how the hospital can say that patient care is your priority, when, in my opinion, it is clearly not your priority.&lt;/CommentText&gt;
